	"notes": [
		{
			"id": "nUlE-1C3g3_rfENzh",
			"markdown": "The Investigator uncovers hidden truths, connects scattered clues, and solves problems others cannot even understand. Whether you are a homicide detective, intelligence analyst, corporate troubleshooter, federal agent, investigative journalist, or frontier marshal, you excel at gathering evidence, reading people, and turning confusion into answers. When the group needs to identify a killer, expose a conspiracy, track a fugitive, or determine what really happened, you take the lead.\n\nInvestigators blend analytical skill, fieldcraft, and social pressure. Some are meticulous forensic experts who solve cases in laboratories and archives, while others work the streets through intimidation, undercover work, or personal contacts. Many campaigns benefit from an Investigator because mysteries, conspiracies, criminal networks, and hidden motives create stories naturally — and someone must be capable of uncovering them. Even in action-heavy games, an Investigator gives the group direction, context, and actionable information.\n\nThe *Detective* is the classic investigator: the homicide cop, private eye, military police officer, or noir-style gumshoe who pieces together evidence through interviews, instinct, and persistence. Detectives excel at solving murders, tracking suspects, interviewing witnesses, and uncovering contradictions in testimony. They emphasize Observation, Criminology, Interrogation, Research, Guns, Intuition, Empathy, and Natural Copper. Common disadvantages include Code of Honor (Professional), Sense of Duty, Workaholic, Honesty, Bad Temper, or Obsession.\n\nThe *Forensic Analyst* reconstructs events through evidence, data, and careful analysis rather than street chases or intimidation. This archetype includes crime-scene analysts, cyber-forensics experts, intelligence researchers, laboratory specialists, surveillance technicians, and archivists. In futuristic campaigns, they may become specialists in digital intrusion, predictive analysis, or mass surveillance. They focus on Forensics, Intelligence Analysis, Electronics Operation, Research, Eidetic Memory, and Forensics Whiz Kid. Typical disadvantages include Curious, Workaholic, Obsession, Insomniac, Truthfulness, or Stubbornness.\n\nThe *Undercover Operative* infiltrates organizations by appearing trustworthy while concealing their true loyalties and intentions. Narcotics officers, anti-corruption agents, criminal infiltrators, intelligence operatives, and social engineers all fit this archetype. Undercover Operatives thrive on manipulation, deception, and adaptability, often balancing criminal relationships against the risk of losing themselves in the role. They rely on Acting, Fast-Talk, Psychology, Streetwise, Stealth, Savoir-Faire (Mafia), Smooth Operator, Social Chameleon, Voice, and Honest Face. Common disadvantages include Secret, Compulsive Lying, Greed, Paranoia, Trickster, or On the Edge.\n\nThe *Profiler* studies motives, predicts behavior, and pressures suspects psychologically rather than physically. Behavioral analysts, interrogators, negotiators, cult specialists, conspiracy hunters, and intelligence interrogators all fall under this archetype. Profilers excel at identifying patterns, understanding emotional weaknesses, and manipulating targets into revealing information. They emphasize Empathy, Detect Lies, Psychology, Interrogation, Intuition, and Observation. Typical disadvantages include Obsession, Curious, Callous, Guilt Complex, Jealousy, or Nightmares.\n\nThe *Frontier Marshal* combines investigative ability with survival skills and combat readiness in regions where law is weak and backup is distant. Colonial marshals, bounty hunters, wilderness lawmen, post-apocalyptic peacekeepers, and ranger-style enforcers fit this role. Frontier Marshals thrive in dangerous territory where they must track criminals, survive harsh environments, and often enforce justice personally. They focus on Guns, Search, Driving, Survival, Leadership, Fearlessness, and practical fieldcraft. Common disadvantages include Code of Honor (Soldier’s), Sense of Duty, Overconfidence, Bad Temper, Pacifism (Cannot Harm Innocents), or Loner.\n\nAn important choice is how specialized you want your Investigator to be. Some focus heavily on technical expertise and deduction, becoming unmatched analysts but weaker in physical danger or social manipulation. Others become versatile field operatives able to fight, infiltrate, interrogate, and survive hostile environments. Most successful Investigators benefit from at least some combat skill, social competence, and mobility — mysteries often become dangerous once the truth starts to emerge.\n\nInvestigators also benefit enormously from campaign-specific knowledge. In cyberpunk settings, Computer Operation, Electronics Operation, and Intelligence Analysis may be essential. In frontier or survival-focused campaigns, Tracking, Survival, Driving, or Area Knowledge become invaluable. In political or criminal intrigue games, Streetwise, Savoir-Faire, Diplomacy, and Contacts can matter more than weapons. Choose skills that reflect the kinds of secrets the game revolves around."
		}
	]
}
